DURBAN – The Office of the Chief Justice has issued a warning to members of the public about an individual who has been impersonating a judge who sits on the Supreme Court of Appeal (SCA).  A statement from the Office of the Chief Justice (OCJ) said that an individual had been impersonating Supreme Court of Appeal (SCA)Judge Nolwazi Mabindla-Boqwana and had contacted persons, and entities purporting to be the judge. The office said the unknown individual sent text messages requesting private and sensitive information related to active court matters, as well as contact information of certain high profile individuals. “We are grateful to our stakeholders for bringing these alleged attempts to solicit such  information to our attention,” the statement continued. The office further warned that impersonating a judicial officer is a criminal offence,  adding that the matter had been handed over to the relevant law enforcement agencies for further handling. The OCJ pleaded with members of the public and media to contact it to verify the authenticity of any communication, directive, article, or social media post that purports to come from a judge. THE MERCURY